All of the feels creating this. So often we focus so much on where we are going that we fail to stop and realize just how far we have come. 

If you would have told this girl 20 years ago she would be working in the fitness industry I would have laughed at you. My dream was always to be a dancer, but I loved people and most of all helping them. I always said my mission in life was to change lives. I didn’t know how or what, but I always knew I wanted to make an impact. 

Fast forward here we are today! Living a dream that I never knew I had until I started creating it. One path led me to the next phase/goal and then the next. 

What you see here is a lot of failures followed by each milestone. More failures than successes, but through it all it taught me lesson upon lesson. The biggest lesson I learned through it all is to keep going. Don’t give up. This life is yours to create. So if the first draft isn’t written as planned then you have the POWER to rewrite it and make it into your own. 

One dream was born after another and I am forever grateful to have the best people in my back corner every step of the way. I would not be where I am right now if it wasn’t for you. You know who you are! ⭐️💫

One promise I made long ago was never to give up. To keep chasing my BIG DREAM in every shape or form. Life is too short to wonder, “what if!”

The moral of the story is that it’s never over. It’s never too late. You can do it today, tomorrow or next week.That’s the beauty of this crazy, beautiful life. You make your own  rules! 

I cannot wait to see what the next 20 years looks like 😌

MOTIVATIONAL TOOLS TO KICKSTART JANUARY OFF ON A HIGH 🙌 NOTE! 

1️⃣ Identify your why! What motivates you to get out of bed in the morning? Longing for change? Your health? Want to feel better? Reduce anxiety/depression? By attaching a reason to your goal is what is going to keep you going. 
2️⃣ Map it out! Set a schedule. What are you willing to commit to each week? Make realistic goals so that you set yourself up for success. Consistency = habits! Start small and work yourself up the ladder.
3️⃣ Have fun! Find what motivates you and makes you happy. Whether that be group classes, one on one training sessions or solitude in your own home with a set plan. The beauty is that there is something for everyone. 
4️⃣ Be kind to yourself and enjoy the process. There will be moments where you may fall off the beaten path, but please give yourself grace and know you are human. It happens. Get back up and keep moving! Perfection does not exist so do your very best and at the end of the day that is what matters the most because life is unpredictable. 
5️⃣ Take time to celebrate your mini wins! Why? Because you should reward yourself for doing a good job. Hard work always pays off! 
6️⃣ Mindset Shift. Love your body and be thankful for having the ability to move every single day. It’s a gift!

Yes tight toned abdominals look great, but the health benefits of having a strong core outweigh it all.

While 80% of peoples goals tend to be aesthetic what they don’t understand is “why” having a strong core is important and the benefits that come along with it. When I refer to your “core” I am talking about both the anterior and posterior chain of your center.  Your core muscles enable you to flex, rotate, extend, and compress the abdomen supporting your organs and spine. This includes your rectus abdominis, transversus abdominis, interior and exterior obliques, multifidi, erector spinae, hip flexors, abductors, and glutes. When this support system of the core/lumbo-pelvic region is strong from the inside out it is amazing what it can actually do to your body. Your core is your powerhouse! It is the foundation of your pillar system. When this is weakened all else compensates, muscular imbalances form and injury occurs.  One of the most common issues is lower back pain from faulty alignment. This stems from muscle atrophy, compensation, excessive sitting, and lack of core strength. When the core is STRONG then your posture improves, organs are supported, dynamic of your exercises change and the strength one acquires over time is amazing to watch! 

Now I want to be clear on something this does not mean go do 100 crunches a day! This means learning how to do abdominal exercises correctly, key components that you should focus on and most of all how to begin each and every workout. When your core is activated from the very start the connection is formed so that when you come standing you are able to keep the sensation/activation throughout your workouts.

Helpful tips on how to get started...
1. Start each workout with abdominal exercises focusing on drawing your navel into your spine throughout. (Exercises coming soon) 
2. Incorporate stability exercises into your routine - guess what? Challenging your balance with a stability ball, bosu, standing on one leg forces the deep intrinsic muscles to activate inadvertently. 
3. Start small and Incorporate 5-10 minutes of core exercises into your morning routine 3 days a week.

Your morning reminder to move your body because YOU CAN! This body, this life is a gift. One that you should never take for granted so treat it right by moving it everyday,  nourish it with nutrients, rest and recover as needed so you can keep going! 

Movement is medicine for the soul⭐️💫🌟

Action or excuses? 🚫 You can’t have both!!! 

As I always say “there is no better time to start than now!” and…… “when something is a priority to you then you “make” time.” 

Time management 🌟 

It’s not a sexy conversation and truth be told so many people don’t realize how much time they truly waste doing things that are not helpful or taking them closer to their goals. The art of distraction is a real thing and many of us are “busy” but not intentional with our time. 

How many wasted minutes do you spend a day scrolling through social media? How much time do you spend binging on Net Flix? How much time do you spend worrying about what other people are doing? 

Believe me there are times when you need to just be and recharge your battery - yes!!!! It’s balance, but I encourage you to take out a pen and paper. Yes, I am a dork like this and really dissect how you spend your time for 24-48 hours. Ask yourself is this taking me closer to my goal or further away???

How you spend your time will dictate your results. We all make time for things when they matter to us. Give us joy, fulfillment, happiness, immediate gratification, etc. 

Sometimes we have to work through the hard things aka creating new habits, patterns, breaking old ones,  trying new things to figure out what works and what does not work. It’s experimentation. It’s living your authentic life. 

If you take anything away from this post I hope it brings light to what can be/ possibility. 

Will it be easy? No! Change is hard! Stepping outside of your comfort zone is hard. However, once you cross that bridge the feeling on the other side is 💪💫⭐️😀! 

I hope you choose growth. If you need a push, a high five, a cheerleader don’t hesitate to reach out because that’s what I want for all of you.

The adverse effects of irregular sleep patterns😌💤

Lack of sleep can have a significant impact on cortisol levels. When the body is not getting enough sleep, it can lead to an increase in cortisol production. High levels of cortisol can result in a number of negative effects on the body, including:

1. Increased appetite and cravings for high-calorie foods: Cortisol can stimulate the release of ghrelin, a hormone that increases appetite. This can make it more difficult to control food cravings and maintain a healthy diet.

2. Weight gain, especially in the abdominal area: High cortisol levels can promote fat storage, particularly in the abdominal area, which can lead to weight gain.

3. Impaired immune function: High cortisol levels can suppress the immune system, making the body more susceptible to infections and illnesses.

4. Increased blood pressure and heart rate: Cortisol can increase blood pressure and heart rate, which can increase the risk of heart disease.

5. Increased anxiety and depression: High cortisol levels can contribute to the development of anxiety and depression.

6. Getting adequate sleep is an important part of maintaining healthy cortisol levels. Aiming for 7-9 hours of sleep per night can help to regulate cortisol levels and prevent negative effects on the body. It’s important to note that sleep patterns are unique to everyone and it’s important to understand what works best for you to achieve optimal sleep.

STRONG TO THE CORE💫

So some things moms never really talk about after having a baby as if it’s like “CODE RED,” is the disconnect that you have with your body, especially your core post delivery. I mean it is only natural, you carried a baby for 9 months, the muscles stretch, organs shift, your hips spread and the weight distribution changes accordingly. 

I mean I trained over 30 pregnant women before actually experiencing it first hand and it brought light on what was going on internally. You can read it in a text book, teach anatomy classes, and apply the tools, but this is one thing I had to experience first hand to really understand. Coming from someone who is very mind body aware, I had to re-learn how to reconnect with my center and this is not something that happened over night. 

This meant A LOT more then doing 100 crunches a day! In fact it meant I had to take it back ten steps further and learn how to rengage my transversus abdominis. 

You are probably saying, “what is your transversus abdominis?” Well... it is the deepest layer of abdominal tissue that holds in your organs like a girdle. It wraps horizontally around your center and serves as that internal girdle/compression to support the lumbo-pelvic region and spine. When this is disconnected you will more often then not hear women and men complain about chronic lower back pain. 

Now one thing to be known is that 2/3 women get a “diastasis recti” which is a split in the abdominal wall. The connective tissue also known as the linea alba overstretches due to the extra abdominal force on the tendon causing a split to happen. When this occurs there is a gap in between your rectus abdominis, better known as your “6 pack.” If there is one thing I can STRONGLY encourage you to do is find a medical professional, pre/postnatal specialist to test you BEFORE undergoing any exercise regiment. Why? Because you do not want to exacerbate the condition.

Pilates on the Stability Ball🌟

Like| Share| Save| this one for later. This is a great way to work the posterior chain of the body. 

Muscles Activated: Hamstrings, glutes, core, back extensors to stabilize.

1️⃣ Bridges - start with your feet directly on top of the ball, plans facing down with your pelvis and spine in neutral position. As you exhale extend the hips up towards the sky forming on long line from shoulder, hip to knee. Inhale to hinge back down and lower. Repeat 15x! 

2️⃣ Hamstring Curls - start with your feet on the ball in your long bridge position. As you inhale extend the legs out forming a nice long line, inhale to draw them back in towards your sitz bones! The goal is to maintain evenness in your pelvis and spine throughout. Repeat 15x! 

3️⃣ Bridge to Hamstring Curls - start with your feet directly on top of the ball, plans facing down with your pelvis and spine in neutral position. As you exhale extend your pelvis up towards the sky forming one long line from shoulder, hip to knee. Inhale extend the legs out forming one long line. Exhale glide the heels in towards your sitz bones and then hinge back down to hover off of the ground. Repeat 10x!

4️⃣ Bicycle Preps ➡️ Bicycles! This is a great unilateral exercise designed to stabilize one side of the body while activating the other. Holy Balance and core activation!!!! Start with the one foot on the ball with your pelvis and spine in a neutral position. As you exhale extend the pelvis up to the sky. Then simultaneously extend the bottom leg long as you develope the working like up to the sky. Inhale reach pull the ball back in towards your sitz bones as you bicycle the other leg back in towards your body. Repeat 10x on each leg!

Some of my FAVORITE ways to recruit the deep stabilizers of the core and pelvis to support the spine by using the BOSU! 

Grab your @bosu_fitness ladies and let’s get to work! 

1️⃣ Single Leg Oblique Twist - starting lying on the bosu with your pelvis and spine supported with your hands placed behind your head and knees bent in, in line with your sitz bones. Lay in extension and as you exhale simultaneously flex and rotate the spine as you pull the opposite in towards your body. Inhale to release and extend the upper body and leg back to the straying position. Repeat 8x each side!

2️⃣ Commandos - this is a great way to activate the anterior chain of the body while forcing your spinal stabilizers to recruit. Start in a long dart position with hands placed on Bosu directly underneath your shoulders. As you inhale lower one elbow down, match the other, exhale press up on one then the other returning to your starting position. Repeat! 

3️⃣ Alt Single Leg Bridges - start lying flat on your back with both feet on the bosu and your palms resting gently by your sides. As you exhale extend the hips and simultaneously lift one leg off. Inhale to lower the pelvis and place the leg down, exhale to extend and lift the other leg. Repeat 20x! 

4️⃣ Single Leg Bridges - start lying on your back with one foot on top of the bosu and the other leg in table top position. As you exhale extend the hips up to the sky focusing on keeping the pelvis and spine neutral and square throughout. Complete 10x on one side then 10x on the other.

5️⃣ Squat Curl Press On The Bosu - start sitting at the very base of the Bosu holding the DB in towards your chest. As you inhale take the shape of the bosu exhale scoop in the abdominals, press in the heels and come to standing as you extend the arms overhead. Inhale to hinge at the hip, lower the body down with the hips at the base of the bosu and repeat 10x.

3 Ways to Use a Yoga Block to Engage Your Core + Aid in Articulation of the Spine💫

I am a huge fan of adding in different props to recruit underutilized muscles. In this little tutorial I want to show you how adding a simple yoga block can aid in articulation of the spine, by simply connecting with your adductors/inner thighs and core on a deeper level. 

1. Half Roll Back - Start sitting on top of your sitz bones with the yoga block in between the knees. Extend the arms out in front of you and as you exhale lead with your tailbone to slowly roll off of your sitz bones scooping in your abdominals. As you inhale lead with the crown of the head and roll forward on top of your sitz bones. Focus on the scooping sensation throughout. 

2. Teaser Prep - Start laying supine with your knees flexed and heels in line with your sitz bones and the yoga block in between the knees. As you inhale, reach the arms up towards the sky and exhale peel up vertebrae by vertebrae to flex the spine forward, then as you come to the top lengthen the spine to form a “J curve.” Inhale to lead from the tailbone to lower down and exhale extend the arms overhead. Repeat. 

3. Hip Rolls - Start laying flat on your back with your heels in line with your sitz bones and the yoga block in between your knees. As you exhale squeeze the block, and slowly start articulating up vertebrae by vertebrae forming one long line from shoulder, hip to knee. Inhale to stay, exhale to lower down mid thoracic, all the way to your lower lumbar and release the sacrum at the bottom.

FIT TIPS🌟

What you should focus on when you are performing some basic abdominal exercises so you are executing with proper form, stability and increasing mobility of the spine. 

Don’t ❌:

➡️ Use momentum to hoist up off of the ground because it puts excessive strain on the abdominal wall and we don’t want a diastasis!
➡️ extend the neck or “leave it behind” when you are curling off of the floor. The goal is to have the head follow the line of the spine at all times.
➡️ pop the abs when the legs are off of the ground, putting excessive strain on the lower back, hip flexors and abdominal wall. 

FOCUS on….

🌟 Increasing mobility of the spine peeling up vertebrae by vertebrae. 
🌟 Keeping the head in line with the spine so when you curl up slightly nod the chin to peel off forming a “C curve.”
🌟 when your legs are lifted off the ground make sure your spine is imprinted. Focus on articulation coming from the tailbone first.

5 Fitness Myths You Need to Stop Believing💫

Myth: Crunches will give you six-pack abs

Truth: While crunches can help strengthen your abdominal muscles, they won't give you six-pack abs on their own. A combination of strength training, cardiovascular exercise, and a healthy diet is necessary for achieving visible abs.

Myth: Lifting weights will make you bulky

Truth: Lifting weights can help you build muscle, but it won't necessarily make you bulky. Building significant muscle mass requires a dedicated focus on training and nutrition, and most people won't achieve a bulky physique without specifically training for it.

Myth: You need to stretch before exercise to prevent injury

Truth: While stretching can be beneficial for improving flexibility and mobility, recent research has shown that static stretching can cause you to lose 30% of your force production before exercise. Instead, it's recommended to perform a dynamic warm-up to prepare your muscles and joints for exercise and of course foam roll!!!

Myth: You need to work out every day to see results

Truth: Rest and recovery are just as important as exercise when it comes to achieving fitness results. Overtraining can lead to injury and burnout, so it's important to allow your body time to rest and recover between workouts. And make sure you are training with purpose, intention and progression. There is a science to the madness. 

Myth: Cardio is the best way to lose weight

Truth: While cardiovascular exercise can be an effective tool for weight loss, it's not necessarily the best or only way. It’s super important that you add in strength training 3-4x a week which will not only change your BMI and help you lose weight by building muscle mass, but will also help you  increase your metabolism and burn more calories at rest.

I share this so that you can make more informed decisions about your fitness routine and achieve your goals more effectively. Remember to focus on a combination of strength training, cardiovascular exercise, and a healthy diet, and to prioritize rest and recovery to avoid burnout and injury.

Meal planning, yes I know it is not the sexiest topic, but I will tell you that it can be a game changer in your life. One that I had to experience first hand for myself to believe it. Now, if you are anything like me you are constantly moving from one thing to another, juggling work, kids, home life and yes the stressors can pile up over time. We all live life on the go, trying to pack in as much as possible and that can leave you feeling limited, stressed and quite frankly cause you to gain weight, feel uncomfortable in your own skin and depressed.   When I learned just how much easier I could make my life and reduce stress in my life I was SOLD! I knew there had to be a solution, which is why I made it my mission to teach my clients and BTF App members just how easy it really could be. You see, I am all about simplifying. Making life easier. Add on the perks of seeing results and having more energy, sleeping better and staying on track. If that means designating an 1.5 hours one day a week to grocery shop + prep then bring it on!   And..... it’s a great way to save time and money, but it can be difficult to know where to start. This is why I wanted to share with you a few steps to help you get started:  
1. Assess your needs: Consider your dietary restrictions, allergies, and personal preferences. Think about the number of people you are cooking for and how much time you want to spend cooking.
2. Make a grocery list: Before you start meal planning, make a list of the ingredients you need for the meals you plan to make. Be sure to include staples like oils, spices, and basic pantry items.
3. Plan your meals: Decide on a menu for the week and make sure you have all the ingredients on hand. Consider using leftovers in new dishes to save time and money. I map this out for you inside of the BTF App with “anytime/postworkout” meals to limit the guesswork.

How to start meal planning💥

Meal planning can be a great way to save time and money, but it can be difficult to know where to start. Here are a few steps to help you get started:

💥Assess your needs: Consider your dietary restrictions, allergies, and personal preferences. Think about the number of people you are cooking for and how much time you want to spend cooking.
💥Make a grocery list: Before you start meal planning, make a list of the ingredients you need for the meals you plan to make. Be sure to include staples like oils, spices, and basic pantry items.
💥Plan your meals: Decide on a menu for the week and make sure you have all the ingredients on hand. Consider using leftovers in new dishes to save time and money.
💥Prepare ahead of time: When you have the time, chop vegetables, marinate meat, and make sauces or dressings to save time during the week.
💥Make use of your freezer: Make larger batches of meals and freeze them for later. This way, you always have a meal ready to go when you’re short on time.
💥Be flexible: Be open to change, if something doesn’t go as planned or if you’re craving something else, it’s ok to switch things up.
🙌Track your progress: Keep track of the meals you’ve planned, the ingredients you’ve used, and how much you’ve spent. This will help you to identify patterns and make adjustments as needed.
💫Make it a habit: Try to make meal planning a regular habit, set aside some time each week to plan your meals and make your grocery list.

Meal planning takes time and effort, but it can save you time and money in the long run. Start small and gradually build up your meal planning skills. With practice, you’ll find meal planning becomes easier and more efficient. Most of all part of your weekly ritual. My motto - set yourself up for success!!

Carbs: friend or foe? 🤔 Let's get to the truth!

🍞🥦 Carbohydrates are an essential part of a healthy diet, providing our bodies with energy and vital nutrients. But not all carbs are created equal! Complex carbs, like whole grains and veggies, provide sustained energy and are rich in fiber. Simple carbs, like sugary drinks and desserts, can contribute to weight gain and other health problems.

Myth #1: Carbs are bad for you. FALSE! Choosing the right types of carbs and eating them in moderation is important.

Myth #2: Carbs make you fat. NOT NECESSARILY! Consuming too many calories in any form can lead to weight gain. It's more likely a result of consuming too many calories in general or consuming too many simple carbs that are high in added sugars.

If you're looking to reduce your carb intake, consider alternatives like cauliflower rice or zucchini noodles. But remember, it's important to include carbs in your diet for optimal health!

Focus on complex carbs like whole grains and vegetables, and limit your intake of simple carbs like sugary drinks and desserts. Let's debunk these myths and enjoy the benefits of carbs in a healthy, balanced diet! 🍎🥕 #carbs #healthyeating #mythsdebunked

Never underestimate the POWER of small movements, muscle activation and props! 

Taking the most basic movements and adding bands, rings, and/or ankle weights can make a whirl of a difference. My favorite part about them is that they really tap into the intrinsic muscle fibers of your core! 

Coming from someone who always had a hard time connecting with my core these were a game changer!!!

Here are just two examples of how you can use them to add just enough load to intensify each movement.

💫Double Leg Stretch - start lying on your back with your spine imprinted and your legs in tabletop position and your hands reaching towards your knees. Place the run in between your ankles to add a little adductor connection and ankle weight on the ankle to add a little resistance. 

As you exhale curl your head, neck and shoulders up off of the floor. Inhale to reach the arms and legs away from each other as you simultaneously squeeze the ring to activate your inner thighs and core. 

Swan Dive - start lying prone with your arms extended long and your hands placed directly on top of the ring. Start with your legs wider than hip distance laterally rotated out to the sides. As you inhale press into the ring as you simultaneously extend the spine getting more range of motion. Exhale to lower down. 

Double tap 🙌 and follow along for more little tips!

The Importance of Rest and Recovery for Overall Health and Well-Being 💤

When it comes to achieving our health and fitness goals, we often focus on the importance of exercise and nutrition. But what about rest and recovery? 🤔

Rest and recovery are just as important as exercise and nutrition for our overall health and well-being. Getting enough sleep and taking rest days can help prevent burnout, reduce stress levels, and improve our mental and physical health. 💆‍♀️💆‍♂️

Sleep is crucial for our body to repair and rejuvenate itself, and getting enough quality sleep can help improve our mood, memory, and concentration. Aim for 7-8 hours of sleep per night to ensure that your body has enough time to rest and recover. 😴

Rest days are also important to give our bodies a break from exercise and prevent overtraining. On rest days, focus on active recovery activities like stretching, yoga, or light walking to help improve circulation and reduce muscle soreness. 🧘‍♀️🚶‍♀️

Remember, rest and recovery are not signs of weakness or laziness, but essential components of a healthy lifestyle. Make sure to prioritize rest and recovery in your routine to achieve your health and fitness goals and maintain overall well-being. 💪💚

The MAGIC 💫 of the Stability Ball! 

Let Let’s Talk Stabilization! Why you should mix up how you train, the many benefits and the long term effects that it has when you cycle it through your program design.

First and foremost, it is important to note that we all have deep stabilizers that surround your core, pelvis and spine. These hold your body upright, allow you to produce more force production, give you power and assist in keeping your infrastructure strong in the body. 

Whenever you are sitting at a machine you are typically isolating one area of your body/muscle group, however when you add in a stability ball, balance board, standing on one leg or perform any unilateral movement you are forced to recruit the entire body aka the stabilizers that hold your body upright. Now, both serve a purpose contingent upon the set periodization that you are currently in, but one thing I will say is that adding in a 4 week cycle with stabilization/strength will not only make you stronger, but will keep your body working as one for body longevity.

You see our bodies adapt over time to things. What once may have felt super hard, is a walk in the park for you now. Why? Because your body adapted. This is why it is key to continue to perform a progression and mix it up over time. This will help build strength, stamina, endurance and stability.

How many steps should you be taking a day to be healthy? 🚶‍♀️🚶‍♂️

When it comes to staying healthy, regular physical activity is key. And one simple way to get more active is by increasing the number of steps you take each day. But how many steps should you aim for? 🤔

Research suggests that aiming for at least 10,000 steps per day can help improve overall health, reduce the risk of chronic diseases, and maintain a healthy weight. Walking regularly can also improve your cardiovascular health, strengthen your bones and muscles, boost your mood, and even improve your brain function. 🧠

If you're not currently hitting 10,000 steps per day, don't worry! You can gradually increase your step count by taking more frequent short walks throughout the day, taking the stairs instead of the elevator, or even parking farther away from your destination. 🚶‍♀️

Tracking your steps with a pedometer or fitness tracker can also be helpful for setting goals and staying motivated. And don't forget to talk to your doctor or a certified personal trainer to determine the right step count for you based on your age, fitness level, and specific health goals. 💪

Incorporating more walking into your daily routine can have numerous benefits for your physical and mental health. Start small and gradually increase your step count over time to reach your goals and maintain a healthy lifestyle. 🌟

The one thing most people skip is the one thing that will keep you moving long term - stretching! ⭐️

This is your little reminder to check in with yourself and make time to STRETCH it out. That beautiful body has been working hard all week and it needs a little TLC to open up the muscle spindles around the hips, pelvis and spine. 

When is the best time to perform your static stretches? 

When the body is warm at the end of your workout. This is why I always ask my clients to leave time at the end of their workouts for a proper cool down. By taking 10 minutes at the end of your workout to perform some basic static stretches will only aid in bringing the body back to a neutral state. I advise that you hold each stretch/position for 25-30 seconds lengthening the muscles, which will aid in maintaining balance in the infrastructure. Believe me when I tell you that this can make a whirl of a difference on muscle recovery, relieving lactic acid build up, avoiding muscular imbalances and most of all preventing injury. My goal is body longevity and this is one thing that should not be neglected after a heavy workout. 

Fun fact: if you do your static stretches before your workout you lose 30% of your force production. 

Happy Monday!

POSTERIOR CHAIN ACTIVATION💫🔥⭐️

One thing I strive for in every workout that I create is BALANCE! A balanced body is a healthy body. When muscles are “over activated” or “under utilized” there is a shift in the force of gravity and pull on the body. This leads to injury over time.

Now more than ever people are spending excessive amounts of time sitting and are leading a more sedentary lifestyle by default. As a result, postural deviations start to form - overactive hip flexors, uneven shift in the pelvis, rounded shoulders, overactive neck flexors, etc. 

This is why I make it a point to work the posterior chain in my workouts. Here are 3 exercises that I incorporate once the body is rolled out, warmed up and moving. 

1️⃣ Bridge Hamstring curl to bicycle
2️⃣ Breast Stroke Prep
3️⃣ Hip extensions 

This is why I love functional training. It keeps your body guessing!

The “POWER of FUNCTIONAL TRAINING”

Why is it important to incorporate agility and functional training into your workouts? 

They both improve balance, control, reaction time, flexibility, posture and overall movement control. Sitting at a machine you are working the primary muscle groups of focus, which is great for hypertrophy training, super sets and those that are more limited in their everyday movements. However the intrinsic stabilizers, core, and surrounding muscle groups are “sitting quiet” as I like to say because they are not directly involved. This is why I believe that is important to incorporate it all!!

Get off the machines and start incorporating all different movement patterns into your workouts to fire up both your aerobic and anaerobic systems and both fast and slow twitch muscle fibers. Your body was meant to move! Push, pull, jump, rotate, lift, and squat. Challenge it! 

Benefits:
*Improve posture and alignment
*Improve stability, strength, muscular endurance 
*Increase your calorie burn
*Train your body to react
*Train all different energy systems so that your body gets stronger both internally and externally 
*Work in all planes of motion
*Incorporate level changes 
*Train outside the box - your body was meant to move!

My end goal for all of our clients is to function at an optimal level. At the end of the day it’s about body longevity, performance and function.

Are you struggling to build a workout routine that is tailored to your needs? Well I've got your back! I have put together a list of tips to help you create a personalized workout routine that aligns with your fitness goals, preferences, and lifestyle. Get ready to transform your fitness game and achieve your dream physique! 💪

First things first, you need to set clear and achievable fitness goals. Do you want to lose weight, build muscle, or enhance your overall fitness? Knowing what you want to achieve is a crucial step towards creating a successful workout routine.

Once you've set your goals, it's time to identify your workout preferences. Are you a cardio junkie? Do you love functional training, pilates, yoga, cycling or do you prefer strength training and heavy lifting? Would you rather workout in the morning or evening? Identify what works best for you, and make sure to factor in your schedule to stay consistent. Remember consistency is key! 

Now that you know what you like, schedule your workouts accordingly. Find a time and frequency that works best for you and stick to it. Remember, even a short workout is better than no workout at all!

It's important to start slow and progress gradually. Don't push yourself too hard at the beginning and gradually increase the intensity and duration of your workouts over time. This approach will help you avoid injuries and build your fitness level gradually.

Mixing up your workouts is also essential to keep your routine fresh and exciting. Incorporate different types of exercises such as strength training, cardio, and pilates. Your body will thank you for the variety! This is something I strive to teach you inside of the @brooketaylorfitapp! 

Last but not least, listen to your body. Your body needs rest just as much as it needs exercise, so make sure to give it the time it needs to recover. Also, if you experience any pain or discomfort, modify your routine accordingly.

By following these tips, you can create a workout routine that works for you, helps you achieve your fitness goals, and improves your overall health and well-being. Get ready to feel the burn and enjoy the benefits of an active lifestyle! 🏋️‍♀️

Meal planning, yes I know it is not the sexiest topic, but I will tell you that it can be a game changer in your life. One that I had to experience first hand for myself to believe it. Now, if you are anything like me you are constantly moving from one thing to another, juggling work, kids, home life and yes the stressors can pile up over time. We all live life on the go, trying to pack in as much as possible and that can leave you feeling limited, stressed and quite frankly cause you to gain weight, feel uncomfortable in your own skin and depressed.   When I learned just how much easier I could make my life and reduce stress in my life I was SOLD! I knew there had to be a solution, which is why I made it my mission to teach my clients and BTF App members just how easy it really could be. You see, I am all about simplifying. Making life easier. Add on the perks of seeing results and having more energy, sleeping better and staying on track. If that means designating an 1.5 hours one day a week to grocery shop + prep then bring it on!   And..... it’s a great way to save time and money, but it can be difficult to know where to start. This is why I wanted to share with you a few steps to help you get started:

1. Make a grocery list: Before you start meal planning, make a list of the ingredients you need for the meals you plan to make. Be sure to include staples like oils, spices, and basic pantry items.

2. Plan your meals: Decide on a menu for the week and make sure you have all the ingredients on hand. Consider using leftovers in new dishes to save time and money. I map this out for you inside of the BTF App with “anytime/postworkout” meals to limit the guesswork. 

3. Prepare ahead of time: When you have the time, chop vegetables, marinate meat, and make sauces or dressings to save time during the week. I usually do this on a Sunday morning when life is a little calmer so that I am set up for success when the week starts. However, my best advice make it work for YOU!

Restoring your electrolytes is something that is crucial for your post-workout routine, and today we're going to discuss why. Electrolytes are minerals in your body that have an electric charge, and they play a key role in many bodily functions, such as muscle contractions, maintaining proper fluid balance, and regulating your heart rate. When you exercise, you lose electrolytes through sweat, and if you don't replenish them, it can lead to dehydration, muscle cramps, and fatigue. That's why it's so important to restore your electrolytes after a workout. You can do this by drinking fluids that contain electrolytes or eating foods that are high in electrolytes, such as bananas, avocados, sweet potatoes, spinach, and coconut water. Don't forget that if you don't replace your electrolytes, you may experience symptoms like dizziness, headaches, and muscle weakness. So, next time you hit the gym, make sure to restore your electrolytes to keep your body in top shape. 

Some of my favorite ways to replenish are @piquelife @drinklmnt @harmlessharvest! 

And if you found this post helpful, please like and share it with your friends. As always, remember to stay hydrated and take care of your body.

“Knee Health: Tips and Tricks for Keeping Your Joints Strong and Flexible”

Truth be told, as we get older the impact on our joints takes a toll - unless you are taking care of your body the right way. 

Some things to ask yourself….

1. Are you working the surrounding muscles of your joints?

2. Are you wearing the right shoes for the right style of training? This will affect your alignment and help/hinder muscle imbalances.

3. Are you mixing up your workout routine? Adding in strength, cardio, Pilates and proper stretching to maintain flexibility and mobility in the joints?

4. Are you making the time to warm up properly aka rolling out and cooling down with your static stretches after every workout?

5. Are you following a progressive program that builds a strong foundation so that your body adapts over time? 

All of this interplays on your joint health. 

To get you started today try adding in these two variations of glute exercises to your workout routine to fire the intrinsic muscles around your pelvis and spine. You may be surprised when you feel muscles you have never felt before or muscles that simply have not been used in quite some time. 

Not only do these types of exercises target your glutes and abductors, but they also elongate the hip flexors for those who spend excessive amounts of time sitting all day. 

The key is to mix it up and keep the body moving - body longevity is always the goal! 

Add these to your workout routine. Ready for more?

How to avoid the sugar cravings…..

One of the 🔝 questions I get asked. Let me tell you sugar is addicting!!! The more you eat it the more you want it. Your body gets used to the extreme serge of energy and then crashes eventually, only to repeat this viscous cycle. 

So what can you do to make a change? Build upon small habits and then attach onto one another. Don’t expect perfectionism over night, but focus on your improvements daily and celebrate your successes!! 

My go to’s:

1. Eat protein at every meal
2. Stop buying processed sugars 
3. Real labels - know what you are eating 
4. Track your tendencies 
5. Avoid added sugars 
6. Fill half of your plate with veggies 
7. Don’t keep it in the house 
8. Strength train 3x a week
9. Move your body a little everyday
10. Get Quality sleep

The POWER of FUNCTIONAL TRAINING”

Why is it important to incorporate stability and functional training into your workouts? 

They both improve balance, control, reaction time, flexibility, posture and overall movement control. Sitting at a machine you are working the primary muscle groups of focus, which is great for hypertrophy training, super sets and those that are more limited in their everyday movements. However the intrinsic stabilizers, core, and surrounding muscle groups are “sitting quiet” as I like to say because they are not directly involved. This is why I believe that is important to incorporate it all!!

Get off the machines and start incorporating all different movement patterns into your workouts to fire up both your aerobic and anaerobic systems and both fast and slow twitch muscle fibers. Your body was meant to move! Push, pull, jump, rotate, lift, and squat. Challenge it! 

Benefits:
*Improve posture and alignment
*Improve stability, strength, muscular endurance 
*Increase your calorie burn
*Train your body to react
*Train all different energy systems so that your body gets stronger both internally and externally 
*Work in all planes of motion
*Incorporate level changes 
*Train outside the box - your body was meant to move!

My end goal for all of our clients is to function at an optimal level. At the end of the day it’s about body longevity, performance and function.

🌱 Revamp Your Diet: Why Rotating Foods is Key to a Healthier You 🌱

Are you tired of the same old meals and feeling stuck in your nutrition routine? It's time to shake things up and embrace the power of food rotation for a healthier, more vibrant you! 🥗🍓🍠

✨ Variety is the Spice of Life ✨

When it comes to nourishing your body, diversity is key. By incorporating a wide range of fruits, vegetables, whole grains, lean proteins, and healthy fats into your diet, you'll provide your body with an array of essential nutrients. But don't stop there! Rotating your food choices can take your health to the next level. 🌈

🔄 The Benefits of Food Rotation 🔄

1️⃣ Maximizes Nutrient Intake: Each food carries a unique set of vitamins, minerals, and phytochemicals. By rotating foods, you ensure you're getting a broader spectrum of nutrients for optimal health and wellness.

2️⃣ Reduces Sensitivities: Constantly consuming the same foods can lead to sensitivities or intolerances over time. By rotating your choices, you give your body a break from potential allergens and minimize the risk of developing food sensitivities.

3️⃣ Enhances Gut Health: Your gut microbiome thrives on diversity. By rotating foods, you promote a healthy balance of gut bacteria, which supports digestion, nutrient absorption, and overall well-being.

4️⃣ Prevents Nutritional Deficiencies: Some foods contain compounds that can interfere with nutrient absorption. By rotating your diet, you minimize the risk of deficiencies by allowing your body to absorb nutrients more effectively.

5️⃣ Boosts Flavor and Enjoyment: Let's face it, eating the same meals every day can become monotonous and boring. Food rotation adds excitement to your plate, keeps your taste buds engaged, and makes healthy eating a joyous experience!

🌟 Fuel Your Travels with High-Protein Snacks: 8 Portable Options with 20g of Protein 🌟

Save| Like| this one for later! 

When you're on the go and in need of convenient and protein-packed snacks, we've got you covered! Check out these options with approximately 20 grams of protein per serving:

1️⃣ Protein Bars: Find bars specifically designed with high protein content. Look for around 20 grams of protein per serving on the nutrition labels.

2️⃣ Greek Yogurt: Opt for single-serve containers of Greek yogurt, which usually provide 15-20 grams of protein. Add some nuts or seeds for extra texture and healthy fats.

3️⃣ Beef or Turkey Jerky: Choose lean beef or turkey jerky as a portable and protein-rich snack. A 1-ounce serving can deliver approximately 15-20 grams of protein.

4️⃣ Hard-Boiled Eggs: Prepare hard-boiled eggs in advance and pack them for your travels. Two large eggs offer about 12 grams of protein, making them a nutritious and convenient option.

5️⃣ Protein Shake: Bring along single-serve packets or pre-mixed protein shakes. Most shakes provide 20-25 grams of protein per serving, giving you an easy on-the-go protein boost.

6️⃣ Cottage Cheese: Grab individual cups of cottage cheese, which typically contain 15-20 grams of protein. Enhance the flavor and nutritional value by adding some fruit or nuts.

7️⃣ Nut Butter Packets: Look for single-serve packets of nut butter like almond or peanut butter. These packs can provide around 6-8 grams of protein per serving. Enjoy them with whole grain crackers or fruit for a well-rounded snack.

8️⃣ Tuna or Salmon Pouches: Opt for pouches of tuna or salmon for a portable protein source. These fish options offer approximately 20 grams of protein per serving and can be enjoyed straight from the pouch.

Enjoy your travels without compromising your protein intake. These high-protein snacks are here to keep you energized and satisfied on your adventures! 🚀✨

🌟 This Is Why Pilates Will Change Your Life 🌟
It’s no secret I am obsessed with Pilates. I have been teaching it for over 20 years and it’s the foundation and base point of my workout system. It is all about realigning the body, strengthening the intrinsic muscles around the core pelvis and spine so that your body works with you and not against you. If you are not familiar with it then here is why you need to try it:
1️⃣ Strengthen from the core: Pilates focuses on building a strong and stable core, which is the foundation for good posture, balance, and overall strength. By developing core strength, you’ll notice improved body alignment, reduced back pain, and increased stability in your everyday movements.
2️⃣ Enhance flexibility and mobility: Unlike many other forms of exercise, Pilates simultaneously works on flexibility and strength. Through controlled movements and stretching exercises, you’ll improve your flexibility, increase your range of motion, and enjoy a greater sense of freedom in your body.
3️⃣ Mind-body connection: Pilates emphasizes the mind-body connection, encouraging you to be present and mindful during each movement. As you engage your muscles and focus on breath control, you’ll develop a deeper awareness of your body, promoting relaxation, stress reduction, and improved mental clarity.
4️⃣ Long, lean muscles: Pilates helps sculpt long, lean muscles without adding bulk. The exercises target specific muscle groups, improving muscle tone and creating a balanced, streamlined physique. You’ll feel stronger, more toned, and confident in your own skin.
5️⃣ Injury prevention and rehabilitation: Pilates is known for its therapeutic benefits and is often recommended by healthcare professionals for injury prevention and rehabilitation. The low-impact nature of Pilates exercises is gentle on the joints, making it suitable for people of all fitness levels and those recovering from injuries.

Suffering from neck pain? 

Try these….

1. Pec Stretch - open up the anterior chain of the body. By performing this on the foam roller it allows the weight of gravity to pull across the chest and lengthen  the muscles into slight extension at the shoulder joint. Feels so good!!!

2. “T” Twist - start prone with your legs extended and arms elongated out to the sides. You head is facing down towards the mat. As you exhale, kick one leg in towards your glute and rotate from the foot, pelvis then hips as far as you can go. Breathe and hold this position then return to center and complete on the other side. 

3. Cervical Thoracic Rotation - start side lying with the legs in 90 degree angles with the top arm extended long. As you inhale reach the finger tips up to the sky and exhale rotate the head, neck and shoulders. The goal is to get both shoulder lying flat onto the ground. Inhale to return to neutral. 

4. Extension of the Spine - start with your wrists placed slightly off the roller with your arms extended out long and legs wider than hips distance. As you inhale extend the spine opening the heart and chest. Exhale to lower and return to neutral. Repeat! 

Which one is your favorite 1,2,3, or 4?

Here’s a secret that no one is talking about……

If you want to build a strong core then you need to get off of the machines. True core strength does not come from doing a million sit ups, but from balance, stability, coordination and unilateral movements. 

A lot of time we form muscle imbalances from our everyday habitual patterns. This causes some muscles to over recruit while others become underutilized. This can cause rotation in the spine, discrepancies in hip placement, extraneous strain on the lower lumbar, shoulder impingements, knee injuries, etc. If this is not addressed then injury creeps up quickly limiting mobility and strength. 

This is why it is so important to incorporate unilateral movements into your workouts through your cycle of periodization. This will help keep the infrastructure strong around the joints, improve core stability and strength and keep you moving with ease! 

Picture this: as you engage in exercises such as lunges, single-arm presses, or one arm rows, one side of your body diligently works its muscles to the max, while the other side simultaneously engages to maintain stability and precision. This regimen serves as a genuine test of strength, equilibrium, and coordination! 💯

You see, by incorporating unilateral exercises into your routine, not only do you efficiently target and develop specific muscle groups, but you also enhance your overall equilibrium, coordination, and functional strength. 💪 

You build power, strength, stability, core and control! Here are a couple of my favorite unilateral exercises that you will see inside of the @brooketaylorfitapp to get your body moving, heart rate pumping, and calories burning. It’s the perfect combination that makes a big impact.

🌟 Understanding Cortisol: The Key to Managing Stress 🌟

✨ What is cortisol?
Cortisol is a hormone released by our adrenal glands in response to stress. It plays a vital role in our body's fight-or-flight response, helping us navigate challenging situations.

✨ The effects of chronic stress….
When stress becomes chronic, cortisol levels can remain elevated, wreaking havoc on our health. It can disrupt sleep, impair digestion, weaken the immune system, and even contribute to weight gain.

✨ Managing cortisol levels…
The good news is, we have the power to manage cortisol and reduce its negative effects. 

Here are some proven strategies:

1️⃣ Prioritize self-care: Engage in activities that bring you joy and help you unwind. Whether it's practicing yoga, going for a walk in nature, or indulging in a good book, find what helps you relax and make it a regular part of your routine.

2️⃣ Practice mindfulness: Incorporate mindfulness techniques into your day, such as deep breathing exercises or meditation. These practices can help calm the mind, lower cortisol levels, and promote a sense of inner peace.

3️⃣ Get moving: Regular exercise is a fantastic way to manage cortisol. Whether it's a high-intensity workout or a gentle stroll, find activities you enjoy and make them a part of your daily routine.

4️⃣ Nourish your body: A well-balanced diet rich in whole foods, fruits, vegetables, and lean proteins can support healthy cortisol levels. Avoid excessive caffeine and sugar, as they can contribute to cortisol spikes.

5️⃣ Get quality sleep: Establish a consistent sleep routine and create a relaxing environment to support deep, restorative sleep. Aim for 7-8 hours of quality shut-eye each night to help keep cortisol levels in check.

✨ Understanding cortisol and its impact on our well-being allows us to take proactive steps in managing stress.

✨ Tag a friend who could use some stress-management tips. Together, let's support each other on our wellness journeys!

Remember, managing cortisol is not about eliminating stress entirely but finding healthy ways to cope with it.

Get Fit Anywhere: Bodyweight Workout with a Bench and Jump Rope! 🏋️‍♀️🏃‍♀️Looking for a versatile workout that can be done anytime, anywhere? Look no further! Today, I’ve got an incredible bodyweight routine that only requires a bench and a jump rope. It’s time to sculpt, sweat, and feel amazing! 💪💦

Complete the circuit top to bottom 3x through 12 reps! Let’s go…..

 1️⃣Jump Rope Intervals: Grab your jump rope and get ready to elevate your heart rate. Jump rope for 1 minute, then take a 30-second rest. Repeat for 5x! 
2️⃣ Squat to Squat Jumps: Begin with a deep squat, then explode upwards into a jump. As you land, lower back into a squat position.
3️⃣ Squat with Oblique Twists: Start with a squat position, and as you rise up, twist your torso to the right, then repeat on the left side. Engage your core and aim for 3 sets of 10 twists on each side, building strength and enhancing your waistline. 
4️⃣ Hurdles Over Bench: Use the bench as an imaginary hurdle. Jump laterally over the bench, landing softly on the other side.
5️⃣ Lateral Abduction: Start kneeling, extending one leg out long with the supporting arm directly underneath your shoulder. As you exhale simultaneously, reach your top arm up and slightly laterally flex as you bring the working leg to meet each other.
6️⃣ Skaters: Leap sideways, landing on one foot while crossing the opposite leg behind you. Leap to the other side and continue alternating.
7️⃣ Pop Squat to Criss Cross: Begin with a wide squat position, then explosively jump up and cross your legs mid-air. Land back into a squat position and repeat, crossing your legs the opposite way.
8️⃣ Reverse Crunches: Lie on the bench with your hands behind the bench. As you exhale, scoop in your abdominals and flex the lower lumbar spine, bringing your pelvis towards your ribcage. Inhale to lower down. Relax your upper body throughout and focus on the initiation coming from the lower abdominals.
9️⃣ Single Leg Lifts: Start kneeling on the bench with your hands directly underneath your shoulders. Extend the working leg long. As you exhale, activate your glute and lift the leg up as high as you can while maintaining a neutral spine.

This is why I want to provide you with four impactful strategies that will help you stay motivated and on track to achieving your fitness goals. Prepare yourself to overcome these obstacles with the right tools, mindset and formula.

🌟 This Is Why Pilates Will Change Your Life 🌟

It’s no secret I am obsessed with Pilates. I have been teaching it for over 20 years and it's the foundation and base point of my workout system. It is all about realigning the body, strengthening the intrinsic muscles around the core pelvis and spine so that your body works with you and not against you. If you are not familiar with it then here is why you need to try it:

1️⃣ Strengthen from the core: Pilates focuses on building a strong and stable core, which is the foundation for good posture, balance, and overall strength. By developing core strength, you'll notice improved body alignment, reduced back pain, and increased stability in your everyday movements.

2️⃣ Enhance flexibility and mobility: Unlike many other forms of exercise, Pilates simultaneously works on flexibility and strength. Through controlled movements and stretching exercises, you'll improve your flexibility, increase your range of motion, and enjoy a greater sense of freedom in your body.

3️⃣ Mind-body connection: Pilates emphasizes the mind-body connection, encouraging you to be present and mindful during each movement. As you engage your muscles and focus on breath control, you'll develop a deeper awareness of your body, promoting relaxation, stress reduction, and improved mental clarity.

4️⃣ Long, lean muscles: Pilates helps sculpt long, lean muscles without adding bulk. The exercises target specific muscle groups, improving muscle tone and creating a balanced, streamlined physique. You'll feel stronger, more toned, and confident in your own skin.

5️⃣ Injury prevention and rehabilitation: Pilates is known for its therapeutic benefits and is often recommended by healthcare professionals for injury prevention and rehabilitation. The low-impact nature of Pilates exercises is gentle on the joints, making it suitable for people of all fitness levels and those recovering from injuries.

💫 If you're ready to experience these incredible benefits and embark on a transformative journey, give Pilates a try! Whether you're a beginner or an experienced practitioner, Pilates has something to offer everyone.

STRONG TO THE CORE💫

So some things moms never really talk about after having a baby as if it’s like “CODE RED,” is the disconnect that you have with your body, especially your core post delivery. I mean it is only natural, you carried a baby for 9 months, the muscles stretch, organs shift, your hips spread and the weight distribution changes accordingly. 

I mean I trained over 40 pregnant women before actually experiencing it first hand and it brought light on what was going on internally. You can read it in a text book, teach anatomy classes, and apply the tools, but this is one thing I had to experience first hand to really understand. Coming from someone who is very mind body aware, I had to re-learn how to reconnect with my center and this is not something that happened over night. 

This meant A LOT more then doing 100 crunches a day! In fact it meant I had to take it back ten steps further and learn how to rengage my transversus abdominis. 

You are probably saying, “what is your transversus abdominis?” Well... it is the deepest layer of abdominal tissue that holds in your organs like a girdle. It wraps horizontally around your center and serves as that internal girdle/compression to support the lumbo-pelvic region and spine. When this is disconnected you will more often then not hear women and men complain about chronic lower back pain. 

Now one thing to be known is that 2/3 women get a “diastasis recti” which is a split in the abdominal wall. The connective tissue also known as the linea alba overstretches due to the extra abdominal force on the tendon causing a split to happen. When this occurs there is a gap in between your rectus abdominis, better known as your “6 pack.” If there is one thing I can STRONGLY encourage you to do is find a medical professional, pre/postnatal specialist to test you BEFORE undergoing any exercise regiment. Why? Because you do not want to exacerbate the condition.

🕒 Food Timing: Maximizing Your Nutrition for Optimal Health 🥦🍎
Did you know that when you eat can be just as important as what you eat? Food timing plays a crucial role in supporting your health and weight loss goals. Let's dive into some valuable strategies to make the most of your nutrition journey. 💪

1️⃣ Plan Ahead: Take control of your meals by planning ahead. Preparing healthy, balanced options in advance ensures you have the right foods available when you need them most.

2️⃣ Fuel Your Workout: For optimal performance, have a small meal or snack containing carbs and protein about 1-2 hours before your workout. Energize your body and crush those fitness goals! 🏋️‍♀️

3️⃣ Post-Workout Recovery: Within 30 minutes after exercising, refuel with a protein-rich meal or snack. This supports muscle repair and growth, helping you bounce back stronger.

4️⃣ Rise and Shine with Breakfast: Start your day right with a balanced breakfast that includes protein, healthy fats, and fiber. It kick-starts your metabolism and keeps you fueled throughout the day.

5️⃣ Mindful Snacking: Choose wholesome, nutrient-dense snacks like fruits, veggies, nuts, or yogurt. Listen to your body's hunger cues and snack mindfully.

6️⃣ Time-Restricted Eating: Experiment with time-restricted eating, where you limit your eating window each day. This approach can promote weight loss, improve digestion, and boost metabolic function.

7️⃣ Evening Eating Awareness: Be mindful of your evening eating habits. Opt for lighter, nutritious meals and allow ample time for digestion before bedtime to support quality sleep.

8️⃣ Trust Your Body: Practice intuitive eating by honoring your body's hunger and fullness cues. Ditch the diets and embrace a healthier relationship with food.

Remember, these strategies are designed to help you optimize your nutrition, but it's essential to find an approach that works best for YOU. Consult with a healthcare professional or registered dietitian for personalized advice.

The Role of Nutrition in Muscle Recovery and Growth 💥

Are you giving your muscles the nourishment they need to thrive? Proper nutrition plays a vital role in enhancing muscle recovery and growth.

Fuel your workouts with the right nutrients! Incorporate lean protein sources like chicken, fish, tofu, and beans to provide your muscles with essential amino acids for repair and growth. Remember, protein is the building block of strong muscles! 💪

⚡ Carbs for Energy:
Don't fear carbs! Complex carbohydrates like whole grains, sweet potatoes, and quinoa are your body's energy source. They replenish glycogen stores, support intense workouts, and aid in muscle recovery. Embrace carbs as your fitness ally! 🌾

🌿 Micronutrients Matter:
Vitamins and minerals play a crucial role in muscle recovery. Load up on colorful fruits and vegetables such as berries, spinach, and bell peppers. These nutrient powerhouses provide antioxidants and support overall health, helping your muscles bounce back stronger! 🌈

💦 Hydration Boosts Results:
Water is the unsung hero of muscle recovery. Stay hydrated throughout the day, especially during and after exercise. Adequate hydration ensures nutrients reach your muscles and helps flush out toxins. Drink up and witness the difference it makes! 💧

⏰ Timing Is Everything:
Timing your meals is key. Aim to consume a balanced meal or snack containing protein and carbs within 30 to 60 minutes after your workout. This optimal window kick-starts the recovery process and replenishes your energy stores. Fuel up for success! ⏱️

Remember, nutrition is the foundation of your fitness journey. Give your body the right fuel to maximize muscle recovery and growth.

The Science and Benefits of Strength Training for Women 🧪💪👩

Many women avoid strength training due to pervasive myths: fears of becoming "bulky" or assumptions that cardio alone is the key to weight loss. However, the scientific evidence tells a different story.

Strength training can be a game-changer for women's health. Not only does it help build lean muscle mass (which in turn boosts your metabolism and aids weight loss), but it also strengthens your bones, helping to prevent conditions like osteoporosis as we age.

* 	Metabolic Boost: Strength training builds lean muscle mass, which increases your Basal Metabolic Rate (BMR). A higher BMR means your body burns more calories at rest, aiding in weight management.
* 	Bone Health: Regular strength training stimulates bone growth, reducing the risk of osteoporosis – a condition women are particularly susceptible to as they age.
* 	Functional Strength: The physical strength gained improves daily life activities, whether that's carrying groceries or chasing after your kids.
* 	Disease Prevention: Regular strength training can help reduce the risk of developing heart disease and type 2 diabetes, according to the Mayo Clinic.
* 	Mental Health: Physical strength can also translate into mental strength, reducing symptoms of depression and anxiety, and boosting overall mood.

In conclusion, integrating strength training into your fitness routine is not just about aesthetics—it's about overall health and longevity. So next time you're contemplating your workout routine, consider incorporating some strength training. Your future self will thank you.

4 Quick Tips to Master Your Push Ups🌟💫

This is one movement that takes time to master, but once you do it truly is one of the best exercises because it activates your entire anterior chain of the body. 

Here are a couple of steps you can start with to progress up….

1️⃣ Kneeling Push Ups - This is the best way for beginners to learn how to recruit all of the right muscles and build up initial strength to handle their own body weight. Start in a prone position laying flat on your belly. Place your hands down in line with your shoulders, activate your glutes, engage your core and press up forming a nice long line from head, shoulder hips to knees. As you inhale, lower your body down forming a 90 degree angle at your elbow, exhale press away. Repeat! 

2️⃣ One leg Push Ups - This is a great way to build up the strength to do a full push up. This is a unilateral movement which means one side of the body is working while the other side is forced to stabilize. It adds more weight load, while still forcing you to recruit your core muscles to avoid rotation and shift in weight distribution. Both sides are forced to work independently of each other. Start out doing 6 on each side and progress as you perfect your form. 

3️⃣ Superman Push Ups - This is a great way to train your body to work in both the concentric and eccentric phase to aid in getting full range of motion. It also adds the extra bonus of activating the posterior chain of the body.

4️⃣ Full Push Ups - Start in one long dart position with your head reaching away from your tailbone. As you inhale lower the body down evenly forming a 90 degree angle at the shoulder, elbow and wrist, then exhale extend the arms back to your plank. Repeat!!

Are you stuck sitting at a desk all day? Suffering from lower back pain? Not sure what to do? I got you! 

Statistics show that as of Sept 2021 the  “average” person sits up to 12 hours per day, particularly those with sedentary jobs and lifestyles. This includes time spent sitting while commuting, eating, and watching television.

As a result the hip flexors aka your illipsoas muscle and rectus femoris overactivates and tightens. This is because it is in a shortened position for an extended period of time. This causes excessive strain and lengthening on the lower back which leads to chronic lower back pain. 

However, if you break up your sitting and move around intermittently throughout the day and incorporate this stretch it will help alleviate your lower back pain. It lengthens the psoas back to a neutral state and allows the other muscles to take over.

Step 2 - is to add in some glute work to stabilize the pelvis so that the muscles are supporting the lumbo-pelvic region.

The Importance of Rest and Recovery for Overall Health and Well-Being 💤

When it comes to achieving our health and fitness goals, we often focus on the importance of exercise and nutrition. But what about rest and recovery? 🤔

Rest and recovery are just as important as exercise and nutrition for our overall health and well-being. Getting enough sleep and taking rest days can help prevent burnout, reduce stress levels, and improve our mental and physical health. 

Sleep is crucial for our body to repair and rejuvenate itself, and getting enough quality sleep can help improve our mood, memory, and concentration. Aim for 7-8 hours of sleep per night to ensure that your body has enough time to rest and recover. 😴

Rest days are also important to give our bodies a break from exercise and prevent overtraining. On rest days, focus on active recovery activities like stretching, yoga, or light walking to help improve circulation and reduce muscle soreness. 

Remember, rest and recovery are not signs of weakness or laziness, but essential components of a healthy lifestyle. Make sure to prioritize rest and recovery in your routine to achieve your health and fitness goals and maintain overall well-being.

Fast forward after many attempts I landed a job one I never expected - as a personal trainer. I knew I loved helping people. I loved movement - anatomy and kinesiology. I double majored in psych and BFA in dance and choreography. I needed to make $ to pay my rent and the stars aligned.

A little core challenger you can do to activate the obliques and deep stabilizers of your center! 

Laying supine on your back, imprint your spine and bring both legs to tabletop. As you exhale edtend the same arm as leg away from your center, while maintaining control in the opposite side. Since it is a longer lever you have more pull on one side than the other so it’s super important to engage the muscles to maintain evenness.

Opposite arm and leg - this is a great modification to work the oppositional pull across the body. The lower vs the upper to activate your center/core. 

They both work a little differently, but serve the same purpose. Unilateral engagement, core activate and control!

Then one of my favorite ways to mobilize the spine and work articulation - hip rolls!!!! 

Double tap 🙌 and save this one! It’s a lot harder than it looks and is great for muscle imbalances.

Full transparency 20 years ago you would have found me in my college dorm room doing 100 crunches on my roommate’s stability ball in hopes to get a “6 Pack!”

Yes, this was before I knew any better. Fast forward 19 years and I can tell you that you can do as many crunches as you want, but it will not give you a “6 Pack!” Yes, working the muscle will make it STRONG, but if you want definition then you have to do a lot more than just crunches.

I am sure you are not new to the phrase “Abs are made in the kitchen.” Yes, what you eat, when you eat and how much you eat will determine what happens around your waistline in conjunction with the way you train.

You will never out exercise a bad diet, which is why it’s important to note that if you truly want to see a change, lose weight, change your BMI then you have to be willing to alter what you put into your mouth and no I am not saying that you need to live off of grilled chicken and salads the rest of your life, but there has to be balance. 

Balanced Nutrition: Seeking change? Look at your plate. It’s not about strict diets but conscious choices. Occasional treats are fine, but daily indulgences? Reconsider.

Awareness First: I urge journaling. Know your consumption. It’s enlightening!

Training Smart: It’s about energy in vs. out. Heart rate monitors? A game-changer. Train in your zones, adapt to daily changes, and track progress.

Functional Training: Not just traditional exercises; functional training engages multiple muscle groups. It’s efficient and burns more.

Equip yourself with the right knowledge and tools. That’s the ethos behind my BTF App. Curious to dive deeper? Let’s chat and learn together.

🔥 Core on Fire: 3 Stability Ball Moves to Ignite Your Abs! 🔥

Looking for a core challenge that combines balance and burn? I got you! :)

Single Leg Bicycles: Place your hands down on the ground with your feet pressing down firmly into the ball forming a nice long dart position. As you inhale pull one leg into your core while the other stays extended pressing in the ball.  Exhale scoop in your abdominals and draw the knee into your center while you extend the opposite leg long.  Now, cycle that leg as you maintain balance on the ball. Switch and repeat!
Single Leg Bridges: Lie flat on your back, bridge your pelvis up to the sky forming one long dart position from shoulder, hip to knee. Lift one leg off of the ball and the other leg extended. As you exhale, draw the ball in towards your glute while extending the other leg long. Keep the height of the pelvis throughout and hips even. Repeat on the other side. 
Lateral Leg Lifts: Lie on your side with your body draped over the stability ball and your hand placed down on the ground. Forming one long straight line from head to toe. Exhale to lift and lower the working leg while balancing on the stability ball activating your obliques and abductors. Complete all reps then switch sides. 

It’s more than just a core workout; it’s a balance test, a stability push, and a full-on core ignition. Who’s ready to try?

The POWER of FUNCTIONAL TRAINING”

Why is it important to incorporate agility and functional training into your workouts? 

They both improve balance, control, reaction time, flexibility, posture and overall movement control. Sitting at a machine you are working the primary muscle groups of focus, which is great for hypertrophy training, super sets and those that are more limited in their everyday movements. However the intrinsic stabilizers, core, and surrounding muscle groups are “sitting quiet” as I like to say because they are not directly involved. This is why I believe that is important to incorporate it all!!

Get off the machines and start incorporating all different movement patterns into your workouts to fire up both your aerobic and anaerobic systems and both fast and slow twitch muscle fibers. Your body was meant to move! Push, pull, jump, rotate, lift, and squat. Challenge it! 

Benefits:
*Improve posture and alignment
*Improve stability, strength, muscular endurance 
*Increase your calorie burn
*Train your body to react
*Train all different energy systems so that your body gets stronger both internally and externally 
*Work in all planes of motion
*Incorporate level changes 
*Train outside the box - your body was meant to move!

My end goal for all of our clients is to function at an optimal level. At the end of the day it’s about body longevity, performance and function.

🌙 The Power of Sleep: Your Secret Weapon for Health and Weight Loss 🌙

Did you know that quality sleep plays a crucial role in your overall health and weight loss journey? 😴✨ Lack of sleep can disrupt hormones, increase cravings, and hinder your progress. It's time to prioritize sleep for optimal well-being! Here are some key insights to help you understand the incredible benefits of a good night's sleep:

1️⃣ The Importance of Sleep:

Quality sleep is not just about feeling rested; it's about supporting your body's natural processes. Sleep helps regulate hormones, boost metabolism, and strengthen your immune system. It's the foundation for a healthy lifestyle!

2️⃣ Sleep and Metabolism:

Did you know that sleep deprivation can affect your body's ability to regulate appetite and burn calories? Lack of sleep disrupts the balance of hunger hormones, leading to increased cravings and overeating. Prioritize sleep for a healthier metabolism!

3️⃣ Sleep Hygiene Tips:

Improve your sleep quality with simple yet effective sleep hygiene practices. Create a soothing bedtime routine, optimize your sleep environment by keeping it dark and quiet, limit screen time before bed, and practice relaxation techniques to prepare your mind and body for restful sleep.

4️⃣ Sleep and Stress:

A good night's sleep is essential for managing stress. Sleep deprivation increases cortisol levels, which can leave you feeling more stressed and less resilient. Prioritize self-care and create a peaceful sleep sanctuary to promote better sleep and lower stress levels.

5️⃣ Sleep and Energy Levels:

Ever noticed how well-rested nights lead to productive days? Quality sleep rejuvenates your energy levels, boosts cognitive function, and enhances productivity. Wake up refreshed and ready to tackle your day with a solid sleep routine!

Embarking on a fitness journey is not always without its challenges. Along the way, we encounter obstacles, hurdles, and moments of uncertainty. This is why I want to provide you with four impactful strategies that will help you stay motivated and on track to achieving your fitness goals. Prepare yourself to overcome these obstacles with the right tools, mindset and formula.

1️⃣ Set SMART Goals: Define Specific, Measurable, Attainable, Relevant, and Time-bound goals. Break them down into smaller milestones to keep your progress tangible and celebrate achievements along the way.

2️⃣ Find an Accountability Partner: Team up with a friend or join a supportive fitness community. Having someone to share your wins, challenges, and workouts with can provide the encouragement and accountability you need to stay motivated.  According to the American Society of Training & Development study, you are 95% more likely to achieve your goals if you have an accountability partner.

3️⃣ Mix Up Your Routine: Follow a progressive program that changes things up every 4 weeks to avoid plateau, boredom and monotony. Explore different fitness modalities and challenge your body in new ways. Variety keeps things exciting and helps you discover activities you truly enjoy.

4️⃣ Track Your Progress: Keep a fitness journal or use a tracking app to monitor your progress. Seeing how far you’ve come can be incredibly motivating. Celebrate milestones, track your strength gains, and appreciate the positive changes in your overall well-being.

💪 Remember, motivation is a daily commitment. Embrace the journey, celebrate your victories (no matter how small), and keep pushing forward. You’ve got this! 💪

5️⃣ Suppression of the immune response, making us more susceptible to illnesses 🛡️

Diet + Your Bodies Natural Response to Foods!

A lot of the time people hear the word “diet” and they automatically think of dietary restrictions, counting calories or living off of salads. 

The definition of diet is “the kinds of food that a person, animal, or community habitually eats.” The sources of foods that you “choose” to put in your body. 

When it comes to diets there is not a one size fits all!
This is why I encourage all of my nutrition clients to do is be mindful of how their body is responding opposed to following what someone else is doing. What works for one person may not work for you. This is a learning curve. Sometimes all this means is thinking outside the box, experimenting with new recipes to keep your palate satisfied and feeding your body as many nutrients as you can. 

If you are feeling tired, anxious, stressed, lacking motivation, or depressed take a look at your diet. Keep a log! I cannot tell you how many people make changes from this alone because they are more cognizant of what they are putting into their bodies. It makes you take a step back and access. 

One thing I always ask my clients “is this taking you one step closer to your goals or one step further away?” “Are you eating for immediate gratification or to fuel your body the right way?” Some food for thought.....

Good nutrition:
➡️ Honest and outcome based
➡️ Improves performance 
➡️ Improves digestion
➡️ Energizes the body
➡️ Changes your BMI

Knowing how to eat, what to eat and understanding that food timing makes a HUGE difference in your results!
